Basis and Dimension
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a unique linear combination of the columns of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 Think about it for a moment.
 Can you justify this claim? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:unique-linear-combination"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the perspective that the matrix-column product 
\begin_inset Formula $I\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 with coefficients from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, what we are claiming is that for any vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

, the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}\label{eq:standard-basis}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

has exactly one solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 By the invertible matrix theorem, this is equivalent to claiming that 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is invertible, which of course is true!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noting that the solution of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:standard-basis"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 we see the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 itself holds the coefficients of the proclaimed linear combination.
 There is nothing ground-breaking about the calculation itself.
 However, it strikes at the essence of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, paving the way for abstraction to arbitrary vector spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given any set of vectors (elements of a vector space), we can now imagine
 elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 as holding coefficients of a linear combination of these vectors.
 This perspective would not be terribly useful, however, if the columns
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 were the only special collection of vectors (from which each vector could
 be written as a unique linear combination).
 As it turns out, there are many such sets.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\{t,t^{2},1+t^{2}\}$
\end_inset

 forms such a set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 Can you verify this? Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:polynomial-unique-representation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 the columns of any invertible matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 form such a set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is invertible, the invertible matrix theorem tells us that for any vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 there is exactly one solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 of the equation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}.
\]

\end_inset

In terms of linear combinations, every vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a unique linear combination of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 In the terminology of the previous section, the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 always has a solution is to say that the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 span 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The linear independence of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 provides for uniqueness (by theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 These are the characteristics of the columns of an invertible matrix that
 makes it a special set—linear independence and span.
 Conveniently, the terms 
\shape italic
linear independence
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
span
\shape default
 have meaning in 
\shape italic
any
\shape default
 vector space, not just 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, motivating the following definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 of a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
spanning set
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{span}S=V$
\end_inset

.
 A subset of a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
basis
\series default
 (of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

) if it is a linearly independent spanning set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the discussion that led to the definition of a basis, we can be sure
 that a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 has the special property that every vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a unique linear combination of the basis vectors.
 However, this property does not automatically transfer to a basis of an
 arbitrary vector space.
 We will need to argue that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a basis of a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is expressible as a unique linear combination of the vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 be a basis for a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 be a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a spanning set, every vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

, including 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is expressible as at least one linear combination of the vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is expressible as at most one linear combination of the vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 To that end, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 has two representations as linear combinations of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=a_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{v}_{n}\quad\text{and}\quad\mathbf{v}=b_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+b_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+b_{n}\mathbf{v}_{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{v}-\mathbf{v}=(a_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+a_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+a_{n}\mathbf{v}_{n})-(b_{1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+b_{2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+b_{n}\mathbf{v}_{n})=(a_{1}-b_{1})\mathbf{v}_{1}+(a_{2}-b_{2})\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+(a_{n}-b_{n})\mathbf{v}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a linearly independent set, the only solution of this equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}-b_{1}=a_{2}-b_{2}=\cdots=a_{n}-b_{n}=0
\]

\end_inset

and therefore the two linear combinations are equal.
 So, given a basis of a vector space, every element of the vector space
 can be written as a unique linear combination of the elements of the basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bases (the plural of basis) have another important property.
 If there is a basis of a vector space with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, then any subset of the vector space with more than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements is linearly dependent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a basis of a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{u}_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $p>n$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a spanning set, each element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{u}_{1} & =M_{1,1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+M_{2,1}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,1}\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
\mathbf{u}_{2} & =M_{1,2}\mathbf{v}_{1}+M_{2,2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,2}\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & \vdots\\
\mathbf{u}_{p} & =M_{1,p}\mathbf{v}_{1}+M_{2,p}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,p}\mathbf{v}_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
M_{1,1} & M_{1,2} & \cdots & M_{1,p}\\
M_{2,1} & M_{2,2} & \cdots & M_{2,p}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
M_{n,1} & M_{n,2} & \cdots & M_{n,p}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

has more columns than rows, so 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 cannot have a pivot in each column.
 By theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:Matrix-Characterization-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, there is a nonzero vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $M\mathbf{w}=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
w_{1} & w_{2} & \cdots & w_{p}\end{array}\right]^{T}$
\end_inset

 be such a vector.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w_{1}\mathbf{u}_{1}+w_{2}\mathbf{u}_{2}+\cdots+w_{p}\mathbf{u}_{p} & =\phantom{+}w_{1}M_{1,1}\mathbf{v}_{1}+w_{1}M_{2,1}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+w_{1}M_{n,1}\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & \phantom{=}\,+w_{2}M_{1,2}\mathbf{v}_{1}+w_{2}M_{2,2}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+w_{2}M_{n,2}\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad\vdots\\
 & \phantom{=}\,+w_{p}M_{1,p}\mathbf{v}_{1}+w_{p}M_{2,p}\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+w_{p}M_{n,p}\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & =\phantom{+}(M_{1,1}w_{1}+M_{1,2}w_{2}+\cdots+M_{1,p}w_{p})\mathbf{v}_{1}\\
 & \phantom{=}\,+(M_{2,1}w_{1}+M_{2,2}w_{2}+\cdots+M_{2,p}w_{p})\mathbf{v}_{2}\\
 & \phantom{=}\quad\vdots\\
 & \phantom{=}\,+(M_{n,1}w_{1}+M_{n,2}w_{2}+\cdots+M_{n,p}w_{p})\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & =0\mathbf{v}_{1}+0\mathbf{v}_{2}+\cdots+0\mathbf{v}_{n}\\
 & =\mathbf{0}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}\neq\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, we have demonstrated a nontrivial linear combination of the vectors in
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that sum to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, showing that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent.
 This fact is important enough to repeat as a theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
If a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has a basis with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, then any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 containing more than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements is linearly dependent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the implications of this theorem, let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be a vector space with basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}=\{\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{v}_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 and consider two subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

—
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 containing fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 containing greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 vectors.
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 cannot be a basis because it has more than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements (which makes it a linearly dependent set).
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 cannot be a basis for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 because if it were, that would make 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 linearly dependent thereby contradicting the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 is a basis.
 In other words, if a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 admits a basis with 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, all bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements.
 This number 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is thus a characteristic of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and therefore deserves a name.
 We call the number of elements in a basis the 
\series bold
dimension
\series default
 of a vector space.
 The trivial vector space, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

 contains only the one vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

 and, by definition, has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

