An arbitrary element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 takes the form 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)=at^{2}+bt+c$
\end_inset

.
 To write 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\{t,t^{2},1+t^{2}\}$
\end_inset

, we need real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\gamma$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha t+\beta t^{2}+\gamma(1+t^{2})=at^{2}+bt+c
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma+\alpha t+(\gamma+\beta)t^{2}=at^{2}+bt+c$
\end_inset

.
 From here, it is clear that we need 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma+\beta=a$
\end_inset

.
